Title:
Satellite Threat Simulation System Using Machine Learning and Deep Learning for Cybersecurity

Abstract

Satellite communication systems play a crucial role in modern infrastructure including navigation, defense, weather monitoring, and telecommunications. However, these systems are increasingly vulnerable to cyber threats such as signal jamming, spoofing attacks, denial-of-service (DoS), and man-in-the-middle (MITM) attacks. This research proposes a Satellite Threat Simulation System that integrates machine learning and deep learning techniques to detect and analyze cyber threats in satellite communication networks. The system simulates satellite telemetry data and analyzes features such as signal strength, packet loss, latency, frequency variation, and encryption status. A Random Forest classifier is used for threat classification, while an Isolation Forest algorithm performs anomaly detection. Additionally, a deep learning neural network is applied to improve threat prediction accuracy. The system includes a Flask-based cybersecurity dashboard with real-time telemetry visualization, attack analytics, satellite orbit simulation, and a global cyber-attack map. Experimental results demonstrate that the proposed framework effectively detects cyber threats in simulated satellite environments with high accuracy. The system can assist researchers and security analysts in monitoring and protecting satellite communication networks.

Keywords

Satellite Cybersecurity, Machine Learning, Deep Learning, Threat Detection, Satellite Telemetry, Anomaly Detection

1. Introduction

Satellite communication systems have become essential for various applications such as global navigation systems, weather forecasting, remote sensing, defense communication, and internet services. As reliance on satellite infrastructure increases, the security risks associated with satellite networks have also grown significantly. Cyber attackers may attempt to disrupt satellite operations through attacks such as signal spoofing, jamming, or denial-of-service attacks.

Traditional network monitoring techniques are often insufficient to detect sophisticated cyber attacks in satellite communication systems. Therefore, integrating artificial intelligence and machine learning techniques into satellite cybersecurity frameworks has become an important research direction.

This research proposes an AI-based Satellite Threat Simulation System capable of detecting and analyzing cyber attacks in satellite communication environments. The system simulates telemetry signals and applies machine learning models to identify abnormal behavior and classify potential threats.

2. Related Work

Several studies have explored the use of machine learning and artificial intelligence in cybersecurity and intrusion detection systems. Machine learning algorithms such as Random Forest, Support Vector Machines, and Neural Networks have been widely used to detect anomalies in network traffic.

In the context of satellite communication networks, researchers have investigated techniques to monitor telemetry signals and detect abnormal patterns that may indicate cyber attacks. Recent advancements in deep learning have also enabled more accurate detection of complex attack patterns.

However, many existing systems lack integrated visualization dashboards that allow real-time monitoring and analysis of satellite communication threats. The proposed system addresses this limitation by combining machine learning models with an interactive cybersecurity dashboard.

3. System Architecture

The proposed system consists of four main modules:

1. Data Simulation Module

This module generates synthetic satellite telemetry data representing both normal communication signals and cyber attack scenarios.

2. Threat Detection Module

A Random Forest classifier analyzes telemetry features and classifies different types of cyber attacks such as DoS, spoofing, jamming, and MITM.

3. Anomaly Detection Module

An Isolation Forest algorithm identifies unusual patterns in telemetry signals to detect anomalies that may indicate malicious activity.

4. Visualization Dashboard

A Flask-based dashboard provides real-time visualization of system performance, telemetry signals, attack statistics, and satellite orbit simulations using Plotly.

4. Methodology

The system analyzes several telemetry parameters including:

Signal Strength

Packet Loss

Network Latency

Frequency Variation

Encryption Status

These parameters are used as input features for machine learning models. The Random Forest algorithm is trained to classify attack types based on these features. Isolation Forest detects anomalies by identifying unusual data patterns.

Additionally, a deep learning neural network model is trained to improve detection accuracy by identifying complex relationships between telemetry parameters.

The system processes user inputs through a web interface and generates predictions about potential threats in the satellite communication network.

5. Results and Discussion

The proposed system successfully detects multiple types of cyber attacks in the simulated satellite communication environment. Experimental evaluation shows that the Random Forest model achieves high classification accuracy in identifying attack types.

The anomaly detection model effectively identifies unusual telemetry patterns, providing an additional layer of security monitoring. The deep learning model further enhances the system’s ability to detect sophisticated attack patterns.

The cybersecurity dashboard allows real-time monitoring of satellite telemetry data and visualizes attack statistics through interactive charts and graphs.

6. Conclusion

This research presents a machine learning and deep learning based framework for detecting cyber threats in satellite communication systems. The proposed Satellite Threat Simulation System integrates threat detection algorithms, anomaly detection, and an interactive visualization dashboard.

The system demonstrates the potential of artificial intelligence techniques in improving the security and monitoring of satellite networks. Future work may focus on integrating real satellite telemetry data, enhancing real-time attack detection, and deploying the system on cloud platforms for large-scale monitoring.

References (Example)

S. Axelsson, "Intrusion Detection Systems: A Survey and Taxonomy," IEEE Journal.

J. Brown, "Machine Learning for Network Security," IEEE Security & Privacy.

Y. Kim, "Deep Learning Approaches for Anomaly Detection in Communication Systems," IEEE Transactions.